
[1]circus

   CIRCUS, n.

   1. In antiquity, a round or oval edifice, used for the exhibition of
   games and shows to the people. The Roman circus was encompassed with
   porticos, and furnished with rows of seats, rising one above another
   for the accommodation of spectators. The Circus Maximus was nearly a
   mile in circumference.

   2. The open area, or space inclosed, in which were exhibited games and
   shows; as wrestling, fighting with swords, staves or pikes, running or
   racing, dancing, quoits, &c.

   3. In modern times, a circular inclosure for the exhibition of feats of
   horsemanship.
